<br/><a href="/db/classes.html?class=3;mid=106799628427064;page=1;howmany=50#106799628427064"><img alt="" title="Use this to create a link to this post" src="/shared/garrowrt.png" border="0" height="9" width="11" /> Link to this post</a>

<br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1" alt=""/></span></td>
<td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%">
<p>In my opinion (this coming from an outside view as my monk is only level 20, but my bard is 65, ranger 57 and necro 53) monks are great to have in a group, IF they are well-played, just like ANY other class. Warriors can suck if they don't taunt and use their /discs effectively. Clerics can suck if they use the wrong heals at the wrong times. Bards can suck if they're dumb enough to stand in front of a mob while it rampages... it's all relative. If a monk really knows what he's doing, he is capable of adding a LOT of DPS to a group or raid AND control his aggro enough to stay alive. Many of the monks that I've grouped with have been knowledgeable enough about their class that they could tank for short times in emergencies also. Many classes can do that if the person behind the toon is knowledgeable. Many of those classes also have a hard time either generating snap aggro or maintaining aggro though. Monks can generate aggro well over a little time and keep it, but snap aggro in a bind is a little more difficult. Bards can generate snap aggro if the situation is right (using bellows for example) and hold the mob off until /disc deftdance wears off, but maintaining that aggro is difficult. As soon as there's a heal/slow/debuff the bard will usually lose that aggro. In summary, it all depends on the person behind the toon first and foremost and secondly the specific situation. <br /> <br />PS This thread is full of some of the worst grammar and spelling I think I've ever had the displeasure to read, but I must say that I have picked up some good info for playing my monk in emergency situations from it.</p>
